==English==

===Noun===


==Etymology==


From [[liminal]] (Latin ''limin-'', ''limen'' meaning "threshold") and [[centric]] (medieval Latin ''-centricus'' < Latin ''centrum'' meaning “a central position”).


== Definition ==


Configurations in which features such as thresholds (or extremities/edges) simultaneously exhibit attributes of the features of centralisation, and may in fact be one and the same; 
shapes where extremities may be considered simultaneously as focal points, and as identical to the focal points.
 

'''Examples of liminocentric configurations'''

* the [[torus]] (a three-dimensional doughnut-shaped surface of revolution)

* a recursive set of [[Chinese Boxes]] (a set of boxes of graduated size, each fitting inside the next larger one)